<seg id=1> Two South Korea soldiers captured during the Korean War, imprisoned for 45 year and finally escaped North Korea </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Seoul, Reuters- South Korean National Security Planning Bureau said the day before that 2 South Korean soldiers once listed as dead in the Korean War recently escaped from the North after 45 year imprisonment. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> A statement issued by the National Security Planning Bureau said that 67 year old Jin Fuji and 71 year old Piao Dongyi (the names are all transliterated) recently returned the South through the third country. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The statement says that the two were captured in the northeast region adjacent to the border by Chinese soldiers. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> It also says that the two were forced to do slavery work in the coal mines in the North before their fleeing. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The Defense Ministry of South Korea listed tens of thousands of lost soldiers as being dead at the end of the Korean War, which lasted from 1950 to 1953. Jin Fuji and Piao Dongyi were among them. </seg>
<seg id=7> The South and North Korea did not sign formal peace treaty, but ceasefire truce. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> They are still technically at war. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> It is quite out of expectation that the two men became relatives by marriage when they are imprisoned in the North. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> The statement says that the second son of Jin Fuji Jin Ningqiu and the fourth daughter of Piao Dongyi Piao Zhengxin got married April 1994. </seg>
<seg id=11> The statement gives no further details. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> An official of the National Security Planning Bureau said that Jin Fuji and Piao Dongyi now were still detained by the authorities to be asked some questions. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> The Defense Ministry said that about 20 thousand South Korean soldiers lost in the Korean War. The Defense Ministry deemed there might be some still alive. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> A war prisoner fled the North said this April that, he knew that there were 50 to 60 South soldiers imprisoned in the North. </seg>
</p>
